<dl id="n05097a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05097a">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05097a"> 97(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cut 6 + 6 + 6 + 1 + 2 + 6 + 6 + 1 / 30 + 4 = 34</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">An extreme, but by no means unique example of the simplification found in modern languages is the English <i>cut</i>, which can serve both as a present and past tense, both as singular and plural, both in the first, second and third persons, both in the infinitive, in the imperative, in the indicative, in the subjunctive, and as a past (or passive) participle; &hellip; and remember, moreover, that the identical form, without any inconvenience being occasioned, is also used as a noun (<i>a cut</i>), and you will admire the economy of the living tongue. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJLN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJLN"><cite title="source">Language: its Nature, Development and Origin</cite></a> (Jan 1922) 333</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
